    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-12-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-12-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="127"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d127">
                <head>127. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_KRW1" type="from">Robert W.
                        Komer</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Special Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BWH2"
                        type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d127fn0"
                        >Source: Johnson Library, National Security File, Country File, Cambodia,
                        Vol. I. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-12-02">December 2, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <persName corresp="#p_BM1">Mac</persName>—</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_FMV1">Forrestal</persName> didn’t get too far with
                        <persName corresp="#p_SPN1">Sihanouk</persName>, who apparently is
                    determined to get rid of US <gloss target="#t_AID1">aid</gloss> missions, even
                    though he might deign to permit some continued <gloss target="#t_AID1"
                        >aid</gloss>. But <persName corresp="#p_SPN1">Sihanouk</persName> seems to
                    be getting more reasonable, and determined not to break with us, since he still
                    wants insurance against <gloss target="#t_ChiCom1">Chicom</gloss>s.</p>
                <p>Despite inevitable appearance of yielding to pressure, our problem remains that
                    of keeping <persName corresp="#p_SPN1">Sihanouk</persName> from committing
                    suicide. So we ought <pb facs="0303" n="276" xml:id="pg_276"/> to take advantage
                    of advent of new Vietnam regime to press them to stop any Khmer Serei
                    transmitting and muzzle <persName corresp="#p_SNT1">Son Ngoc Thanh</persName>
                    (as <persName corresp="#p_FMV1">Forrestal</persName> proposes in Phnom Penh
                        435).<note n="1" xml:id="d127fn1">
                        <ref target="#d123">Document 123</ref>.</note> Latest is that transmitter
                    may not be in VN after all.</p>
                <p>Geneva-type conference on Cambodian neutrality is trickier, even if <persName
                        corresp="#p_SPN1">Sihanouk</persName> seems to be relaxing on “guarantees.”
                    But one may well be inevitable; <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>
                    and <persName corresp="#p_HRJ1">Hilsman</persName> think so too.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">RWK</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
